<p>The above table is for <i>drop</i> = −12&#160;cm, where</p>
<dl>
<dd><i>drop</i> = <i>waist girth</i> − <i>chest girth</i>.</dd>
</dl>
<p>Example: While manufacturers will typically design clothes for <i>chest girth</i> = 100&#160;cm such that it fits <i>waist girth</i> = 88&#160;cm, they may also want to combine that <i>chest girth</i> with neighbouring <i>waist girth</i> step sizes 84&#160;cm or 92&#160;cm, to cover these drop types (−16&#160;cm and −8&#160;cm) as well.</p>
